            <li>&rarr; <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/sales-professionals/commercial-real-estate-brokers/">CRE broker mortgage guide</a></li>
            <li>&rarr; <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-calculator/">100+ mortgage calculators</a></li>
            <li>&rarr; <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/purchase-inquiry/">Start your pre-approval</a></li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">01</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">What changed in real estate transactions after the August 2024 NAR settlement?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Three changes effective Aug 17, 2024: (1) listing brokers may not offer compensation on MLS; (2) buyer&rsquo;s agents must execute written buyer agency agreement before showing any property; (3) commission negotiation now transparent in the written agreement. Cooperative compensation continues off-MLS.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">02</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Do I have to pay my buyer&rsquo;s agent directly now?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Not necessarily. The written agreement specifies the compensation, but in most Florida transactions sellers continue offering cooperative compensation off-MLS. Contract negotiation typically resolves who pays. Buyer-paid is one option but not the default.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">03</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">What&rsquo;s the difference between a transaction broker and a single agent in Florida?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Transaction broker (default in Florida) facilitates the transaction without exclusive representation. Single agent provides exclusive representation with full fiduciary duties (loyalty, confidentiality, obedience, full disclosure, accounting, skill care diligence). Single-agent representation requires written designation.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">04</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">How do I know if my Realtor is the right fit for my situation?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Look for relevant designations (CRS, SRES, MRP, CIPS, ABR, RENE), substantial transaction volume in your geography, brokerage affiliation, and prior client references. Interview multiple Realtors before signing buyer agency agreement.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">05</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">What does my Realtor do during the inspection phase?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Your Realtor recommends a licensed Florida home inspector, coordinates inspection date and access, reviews the report, and negotiates repair credits or contract modifications. Florida inspection contingency typically 10-15 days. The Realtor manages contingency timing and post-inspection renegotiation.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">06</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">How does my Realtor coordinate with my mortgage lender?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Realtor + lender coordination spans pre-approval, contract financing terms, appraisal coordination, financing contingency timing, conditions clearing, Closing Disclosure 3-day review under CFPB TRID rules, and closing-day execution. Stairway works with Florida Realtor partners across Broward, Miami-Dade, Palm Beach, and the Treasure Coast.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">07</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">What is FIRPTA and when does my Realtor need to address it?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">FIRPTA (Foreign Investment in Real Property Tax Act) imposes IRS withholding requirements on real property purchases from foreign sellers (non-U.S. tax residents). Withholding typically 15% of purchase price unless reduced through certification. Florida transactions involving foreign sellers require FIRPTA compliance coordination. Realtors with CIPS designation commonly carry FIRPTA expertise.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">08</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">How does the Florida condo regulatory framework affect my purchase?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Florida condo associations are subject to Structural Integrity Reserve Studies (SIRS), milestone inspection (10-25 years depending on building), and reserve funding requirements. Estoppel certificates document association financial status, special assessments, and reserve compliance. Realtors in condo communities require expertise in association documentation.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">09</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">How does my Realtor handle the closing process at the title company?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Florida closings handled by title companies or attorneys depending on county practice. Your Realtor coordinates with the title company through document collection, deed preparation, title insurance ordering, settlement statement review, and closing-day execution. Pre-closing walkthrough 24-48 hours before closing verifies property condition matches contract terms.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">10</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I&rsquo;m a Realtor. Can Stairway help with my own home mortgage?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Yes &mdash; Stairway specializes in Realtor-as-borrower mortgages. Real estate agents typically operate as 1099 commission earners with Schedule C structure. We document the multi-year commission history with Form 1084 cash-flow addback recovery under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.5-01/underwriting-factors-and-documentation-self-employed-borrower" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">B3-3.3-02</a>. See our <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/sales-professionals/real-estate-agent/">Realtor mortgage guide</a> for the full Realtor-as-borrower documentation framework.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

